%N A390146 Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of heapable permutations of length n whose longest decreasing subsequence has length k.
%C A390146 A permutation [1...n] is heapable if it can be sequentially inserted into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A390146 The longest decreasing subsequence (LDS) of a heapable permutation is a (not necessarily contiguous) subsequence of the given sequence in which the elements are in strictly decreasing order and the subsequence is as long as possible.
